{"mcp_tool":"mcd_search","arguments":{"query":"aerodynamic road-load basis drag coefficient range CdA aerodynamic road-load", "kind":"markdown","limit":5}}
{"mcp_tool":"mcd_query","arguments":{"sql":"with variant as (select variant_id, curb_mass_kg, drag_coefficient, frontal_area_m2, (cast(drag_coefficient as real) * cast(frontal_area_m2 as real)) as baseline_cda_m2, ((cast(drag_coefficient as real) + 0.020) * cast(frontal_area_m2 as real)) as new_cda_m2, (((cast(drag_coefficient as real) + 0.020) * cast(frontal_area_m2 as real)) - (cast(drag_coefficient as real) * cast(frontal_area_m2 as real))) as delta_cda_m2, (100.0 * ((((cast(drag_coefficient as real) + 0.020) * cast(frontal_area_m2 as real)) - (cast(drag_coefficient as real) * cast(frontal_area_m2 as real))) / (cast(drag_coefficient as real) * cast(frontal_area_m2 as real)))) as pct_change_cda from vehicle_variant_configuration_specs where lower(variant_id)=lower('OAM-V0320')) select * from variant"}}
{"answer":"For OAM-V0320, curb_mass_kg stays unchanged at the variant's recorded value, so rolling/inertial mass terms do not change; the range impact comes from the aerodynamic road-load basis instead. The dossier's aerodynamic basis uses CdA = drag_coefficient × frontal_area_m2, so increasing drag_coefficient directly increases CdA and therefore aerodynamic drag/load at speed. For OAM-V0320, the source row has variant_id=OAM-V0320, drag_coefficient=0.31, frontal_area_m2=2.84, curb_mass_kg=2208, baseline CdA=0.8804 m2, and with a +0.020 Cd increase the new drag_coefficient=0.33 and new CdA=0.9372 m2. That is a delta_CdA of +0.0568 m2, which is a +6.45% increase versus baseline. Because aerodynamic road load scales with CdA, the vehicle needs more power/energy to overcome air drag at the same speed, so range decreases even though curb_mass_kg is unchanged."}
